I've always loved Graze's location on the ped mall where you can sit outside during summer months and the wall is opened to the beautiful downtown community. And Graze's eclectic brunch is my all time favorite in Iowa city.  They offer wide variety of delicious, high quality, healthy and tasty options. I love the soup, bib lettuce wraps, chocolate fountain with fruit, pizzas, tropical burgers and all the other brunch amazingness. But my appreciation for GRAZE just magnified exponentially this week when I was volunteering at Free Lunch and GRAZE delivered hundreds and hundreds of Sweedish meatballs!  They were gourmet and just so beautifully prepared.  No doubt this was an expensive, and time-consuming undertaking...but they reached out to Free Lunch to offer their services and resources and contributed with tremendous grace. The people we served were beyond thrilled with their meatballs.  Many came up to give us kudos for the exceptionally  wonderful lunch, and so many asked for seconds.  I just loved the smiles Graze produced this day.  One guy approached us with a huge smile and said, 'if I was wearing lipstick, both of my ears would be red!' I learned that Graze is trying to keep its staff employed and because of the Corona pandemic, he's paying his staff to support the community. They donated enough Swedish meatballs to serve TWO community lunches.  I'll admit that I snuck 6 Swedish Meatballs home to share with my uncle and son. They fought over these meatballs because they were so good! While I've always loved Graze's food...to me the best spice is community investment and Graze just elevated to the top of my Iowa City Favorites list. I now plan to visit Graze beyond the Sunday brunch and birthday visits (did I mention they have big A-- cakes served with fireworks?!) Check Graze out...they're worth every penny!

When we walked into the restaurant the sign says “Let us seat you”.  It was 5:50pm. The hostess (whose body language says she clearly hates customers) says to us “We have reservations at 7:30 and have a full restauant at that time so we probably won’t be able to seat you.” No hello. No nothing. No do you have reservations?  No greeting.  Didn’t even look at her lil iPad or even ask us if we had reservations, which we did at 6pm.  After educating her on that she says “oh”. Grabs four menus and starts walking.  There were 7 people in the whole restaurant when we came in. After we sat, we ordered drinks.  The server brought us a drink with a little fruit fly floating in it. Didn’t comp the drink or anything, just made a new one and apologized. So this drink passed the bartender AND the server before we, the customer, discovered the insect.  At least the kitchen knows what they’re doing.  We probably won’t be coming back to a place we once enjoyed.

Graze is a boutique martini bar. I've visited a handful of times over the years and the service has always been top-notch. Martinis and cocktails are also on-point. Atmosphere is the most cosmopolitan you can get in IC. But in such a small space you won't have an immense kitchen, so you can't expect anything more than "high-priced" pub food. I've had the buffet and a dinner or two, and the cuisine still has a cosmopolitan finish. But at its core it's pub food. So enjoy the location, the atmosphere, the drinks and the staff. Unique concept with the "Graze" option at $20/person. Prix fixe three course: #1 pretzel with fondue #2 Caesar salad, spring rolls and bruschetta #3 Chicken lips, short ribs and green beans The cheese fondue accompanying the pretzel nuggets were amazing. The pretzel nuggets were overly hot probably from a quick microwave zap. This is my second time having the Graze prix fixe with friends. Both times I find the second course trio a bit oddly matched. The spring rolls are very nicely done and close to ones you would get at a Dim Sum shop. The three dishes add up to a rather overwhelming oily and salty taste. The third course shines through the melt in your mouth short ribs that flake off the bone and the sichuan inspired sauteed green beans . All in the all, the Graze option is a great starter for someone new to Graze.
